			</td><td width="2%">&nbsp;</td><td width="44%"> Abstract
			<div style="text-align:justify;">
				<P>
					<B>Introduction</B>: The fundamental right to health denotes a prestacional duty of the State. Despite the poor management of public resources available for achieving this vital law, the fact that the high number of traffic accidents corroborates to an accentuation of state spending, which could be allocated, for example, in the treatment of diseases inevitable from the point of view institutional. One should not forget that the published statistics do not point solely to the number of traffic accidents and spending on expenses related to public health arising from such events, but also reveal the absence of state actions aimed at prevention and reduction, respectively. In the current situation of the Brazilian state, it is up to him the task of putting the fundamental rights provided in the Constitution, among them health if outweighs. For this to be made possible, one must necessarily proceed with the implementation of effective public policies for the prevention of traffic accidents and thus contribute to the reduction of their costs					<B>Objectives</B>: Constitute objectives of this research the analysis of statistics related to traffic accidents and their interference in the state budget , celing considering public spending for health , in order to pursue issues of evidence wrapped in not adopting state actions and effective public policies in accident prevention, supposedly clever instruments to reduce the amount spent with their expenses incurred and that allow the state to reallocate public resources available to promote the realization of the right .					<B>Methods</B>: Transversal study conducted by collecting data available on the website of the Health Information System , the Ministry of Health of the Federal Government, regarding the characteristics of accident victims in traffic, especially in terms of gender , in addition to its number of admissions in public health system and care costs in the north, Northeast , Midwest , Southeast and south, during the twelve months of 2011 , with a view to ascertaining the impact of public expenditure spent on the cost of hospital expenses from the traffic accidents at the expense of ensuring the right to health in Brazil.					<B>Results</B>: The results of this research are reflected in the data obtained from the Ministry of Health of the Federal Government, celing System of the SUS Hospital Information (SIH / SUS), so follow below.
Table 1, in contemplating the hospital morbidity (hospitalization rate) of the Unified Health System by external causes, according to place of residence of patients, especially those caused by traffic accidents in the year 2011, revealed that the male gender It is involved in most instances, with a total of 135,697 cases or 77.94% relative to the total. The feminine gender is represented in 22.06% of cases, which corresponds to 38,418 events.
In all, 174 115 cases recorded in that period.
Furthermore, it could be seen that the highest incidence of traffic accidents in the observed period, occurred in the southeastern region, which had 76,943 records (44.19%), followed by the northeast with 45,777 occurrences (26.29					<B>Conclusion</B>: Investing in effective and skilled programs to lower the statistics presented here does not mean only save , but mostly safeguarding the lives of road users , as well as allowing greater access of citizens to public health quality.				</P>
